<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910306-0052</DOCNO><DOCID>910306-0052.</DOCID><HL>   Politics andamp; Policy:   Belgium Approved Export   Of Dutch Material to Iraq   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>03/06/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   EUROP MDEST N.DLI</CO><IN>INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><LP>   BRUSSELS -- The Belgian government approved the export ofDutch night-vision equipment to Iraq despite a ban on suchexports and U.S. objections, an economics ministry officialsaid.   The infrared visors, which rely on U.S. technology, wereused by Iraqi troops during the Gulf war, specifically duringthe Iraqi attack on the Saudi border town of Khafji, one ofthe first ground clashes.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;Indeed, Belgium provided an export license,&quot; economicsministry spokesman Filip Demeyer told the daily De Morgen. Helater confirmed his statement but refused to elaborate.   In January, the U.S. accused the Netherlands of illegalarms exports and canceled all military contracts with DelftInstruments N.V., which made the visors. The Dutch companyhad sent the visors to Iraq through its Belgian affiliate OIPInstrubel.   De Morgen reported that Mr. Demeyer said the Belgiangovernment approved shipments in 1984 and 1989 to Iraq. DelftInstruments said over the weekend that at least one shipmentwas made in 1990. The Belgian government made no mention ofapproving an export license last year.</TEXT></DOC>